Defines the `ctx-verify` argv surface (via `clap::Parser`) and renders its `Report` to a writer — either the default terse human format or the full JSON contract behind `--json`.

`Cli` fields drive scoping: `package` maps to cargo's `-p` (whole-workspace when absent), `max_diagnostics` caps retained diagnostics per check (default 20), `checks` restricts to a named subset (comma-separated, empty = full default gate), `json` switches output mode. `run<R: Runner, W: Write>(runner: &R, cli: &Cli, out: &mut W) -> Result<bool, CheckError>` is the entry point: builds the report via `checks::run_selected`, writes it to `out`, and returns whether the run passed (`Status::Pass`). Errors are only ever `CheckError::Encode` (JSON serialization) or `CheckError::Write` (I/O to `out`) — check failures themselves are data in the report, not `Err`.

Terse rendering (`render_terse`) emits a single `pass` line when the whole report passes; otherwise one block per non-pass, non-skipped check. Each block (`render_check`) headers with `FAIL:`/`ERROR:` plus a count, then one line per diagnostic with the `file:line` locator left-padded to the widest locator in that check (column alignment is per-check, not global), followed by `lint: message` or bare `message` if `lint` is empty. Diagnostic messages are clipped to `MAX_MSG` (100 chars) with a trailing `…`; a `truncated` count beyond `max_diagnostics` renders as `… +N more`.

Coupling: the JSON branch is a direct `serde_json` dump of `Report`/`CheckReport`/`Diagnostic` from `model.rs` — that struct shape is the wire contract consumed by ctx-run/CI, so field renames there must be coordinated. The terse format has no such contract and can change freely.